<Section title="Rigid bodies" id="rigid_bodies">

    A <em>rigid body</em> is an extended area of material that
          includes all the points inside it, and which moves so that
          the distances and angles between all its points remain
          constant. The location of a rigid body can be described by
          the position of one point \(P\) inside it, together with the
          rotation angle of the body (one angle in 2D, three angles in
          3D).
  <DisplayTable id="rigid-body-table1">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th></th>
        <th>location description</th>
        <th>velocity description</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <th>point mass</th>
        <td>position vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{r}_P" /></td>
        <td>velocity vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{v}_P" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
        <th>rigid body in 2D</th>
        <td>
            position vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{r}_P" />
            <br />
            angle \(\theta\)
        </td>
        <td>
            velocity vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{v}_P"/>
            <br />
            angular velocity <InlineEquation equation="\\omega" />
        </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>rigid body in 3D</th>
        <td>
            position vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{r}_P"/>
            <br />
            angles <InlineEquation equation="\\theta,\\phi,\\psi"/>
        </td>
        <td>
            velocity vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{v}_P"/>
            <br />
            angular velocity vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{\\omega}" />
        </td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
            
    </DisplayTable>

    <p>
        Neither point masses nor rigid bodies can physically exist,
        as no body can really be a single point with no extent, and
        no extended body can be exactly rigid. Despite this, these
        are very useful models for mechanics and dynamics.
      </p>
</Section>

<SubSection title="Rotating rigid bodies" id="rotating_rigid_bodies">

    <p>
        All points on a rigid body have the same angular rotation
        angles, as we can see on the figure below. Because the
        angular velocity is the derivative of the rotation angles,
        this means that every point on a rigid body has the same
        angular velocity <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{\\omega}" />, and also the same angular
        acceleration <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{\\alpha}" />.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 2D the angle <InlineEquation equation="\\theta" /> of a rigid body the angle of
        rotation from a fixed reference (typically the <InlineEquation equation="\\hat\\imath" />
        direction), measured positive counter-clockwise. The angular
        velocity is <InlineEquation equation="\\omega = \\dot\\theta" /> and the angular
        acceleration is <InlineEquation equation="\\alpha = \\dot\\omega = \\ddot\\theta"/>. The
        vector versions of these are <InlineEquation equation="\\vec\\omega = \\omega \\, \\hat{k}" />
        and <InlineEquation equation="\\vec\\alpha = \\alpha\\,\\hat{k}" />, where <InlineEquation equation="\\hat{k}" /> is the
        out-of-plane direction.
      </p>
	  
	  <PrairieDrawCanvas id="rkg-fw-c" height="600" width="600">
        <p class="controls">
            <button class="anim-toggle:rkg-fw-c" onclick="rkg_fw_c.toggleAnim()">animation</button>
            <button class="reset:rkg-fw-c" onclick="rkg_fw_c.reset()">reset</button>
            Show:
            <button class="option-toggle:rkg-fw-c:showAngles" onclick="rkg_fw_c.toggleOption('showAngles')">angles</button>
            <button class="option-toggle:rkg-fw-c:showAngVels" onclick="rkg_fw_c.toggleOption('showAngVels')">angular velocities</button>
          </p>
          <p class="figureCaption">
            All points on a rigid body rotate at the same rate. Body
            <InlineEquation equation="\\mathcal{B}_1" /> is rotated by angle \(\theta_1\), so its
            angular velocity is <InlineEquation equation="\\omega_1 = \\dot{\\theta}_1" />, and
            similarly for the second body.
          </p>
      </PrairieDrawCanvas>
	  
	  
	  <Warning title="Labeling angular quantities on rigid bodies." id="rkg-ww">
      <p>
         Angular quantities (<InlineEquation equation="\\theta , \\omega , \\alpha"/>)for rigid bodies should not be labeled with points. If <b>P</b> and <b>Q</b> are points on a rigid body, we do not write <InlineEquation equation="\\omega_P"/> or <InlineEquation equation="\\omega_Q"/> for the angular velocity about these points.
      </p>
	  <p>
		Instead, we label angular quantities according to the body. If we have two rigid bodies <InlineEquation equation="B_1"/> and <InlineEquation equation="B_2"/>, then <InlineEquation equation="\\omega_1"/>  is the angular velocity of the first body (and all points on it) and <InlineEquation equation="\\omega_2"/> is the angular velocity of the second body.
	  </p>
     </Warning>
	
	
	
      <CalloutContainer slot="cards">
          <CalloutCard>
            <p>
                Rotations in 3D are significantly more complicated than
                rotations in 2D. Unlike positions, velocities, etc, which
                simply go from 2D vectors to 3D vectors, rotational
                quantities go from scalars in 2D to full 3D vectors in
                3D. Angular velocity and angular acceleration are somewhat
                straightforward, so equations <a
                href="#rkg-er">#rkg-er</a> hold in both 2D and 3D, but
                understanding the rotations themselves is significantly
                more complicated. There are three main ways that 3D
                rotations can be represented:
              </p>
              <Enumerate>
                <Item><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_angles">Euler angles</a></Item>
                <Item><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_matrix">Rotation matrices</a></Item>
                <Item><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternions">Quaternions</a></Item>
              </Enumerate>
              <p>
                Detailed study of rotations in 3D is necessary for a full
                understanding of topics ranging from <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attitude_control_(spacecraft)">satellite
                attitude control</a> to <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Articulated_robot">articulated
                robot construction</a>, and is usually covered in advanced
                dynamics courses.
              </p>
          </CalloutCard>
      </CalloutContainer>
</SubSection>

<SubSection title="Points on rigid bodies"  id="points_rigid_bodies">

    <p>
        If we know how one point \(P\) on a rigid body is moving and
        we also know how the body is rotating, then we can calculate
        the movement of any other point \(Q\) on the same body. The
        formulas for this are given below.
    </p>

    <DisplayEquationCustom background="True" derivation="True" title="Rigid body point relations." id='rkg-er'>
        <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}\\vec{r}_Q &amp;= \\vec{r}_P + \\vec{r}_{PQ} \\\\\\vec{v}_Q &amp;= \\vec{v}_P+ \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ} \\\\\\vec{a}_Q &amp;= \\vec{a}_P+ \\vec{\\alpha} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ}+ \\vec{\\omega} \\times (\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ})\\end{aligned}" />
        <p class="m-0">
            Points \(P\) and \(Q\) are two locations on a rigid
            body. Vectors <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{\\omega}" /> and <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{\\alpha}" /> are the
            angular velocity and angular acceleration of the rigid
            body.
        </p>

        <div slot="derivation">
            <p>
                The first equation is simply the definition of the
                offset vector <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{r}_{PQ}" />. Differentiating the first
                equation gives
  
                <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}  \\vec{r}_Q &amp;= \\vec{r}_P + \\vec{r}_{PQ} \\\\  \\dot{\\vec{r}}_Q &amp;= \\dot{\\vec{r}}_P  + \\dot{\\vec{r}}_{PQ} \\\\  \\vec{v}_Q &amp;= \\vec{v}_P  + \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ},  \\end{aligned}" />
  
                where the derivative of <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{r}_{PQ}" /> comes from the <a
                href="rkr.html#rkr-ew">rotation formula</a>, given that
                this offset vector is simply rotating with the rigid
                body.
              </p>
              <p>
                If we differentiate again then we obtain
  
                <DisplayEquation equation="\\begin{aligned}  \\vec{v}_Q &amp;= \\vec{v}_P  + \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ} \\\\  \\dot{\\vec{v}}_Q &amp;= \\dot{\\vec{v}}_P  + \\dot{\\vec{\\omega}} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ}  + \\vec{\\omega} \\times \\dot{\\vec{r}}_{PQ} \\\\  \\vec{a}_Q &amp;= \\vec{a}_P  + \\vec{\\alpha} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ}  + \\vec{\\omega} \\times (\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ}),  \\end{aligned}" />
  
                where we use the fact that <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{\\alpha} = \\dot{\\vec{\\omega}}" />.
              </p>
        </div>
    </DisplayEquationCustom>

    <Warning id="rkg-wc" title="Cross product order">
        <p>
            Because cross products are <a
            href="/dyn/vector_calculus#rvv-wc">not associative</a>, it is very
            important to compute the centripetal acceleration term
            with the parentheses as shown. That is, we must not
            compute <InlineEquation equation="(\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{\\omega}) \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ}" />, as this is always zero.
          </p>
    </Warning>

    <p>
        The term <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{\\omega} \\times (\\vec{\\omega} \\times \\vec{r}_{PQ})" /> in the acceleration equation above is called
        the <em>centripetal</em> (center-seeking) term, as it is
        always in the direction <InlineEquation equation="-\\vec{r}_{PQ}" /> and so acts from \(Q\)
        towards the “center” \(P\).
      </p>

