<SubSubSection title="Knee Joint"  id="knee_joint">
    <p>
      The human knee joint is a type of biological <a
      href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hinge_joint">hinge</a>,
      which allows movement in only one primary angle. The knee
      connects the <a
      href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Femur">femur</a> (the
      upper leg bone) to the <a
      href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tibia">tibia</a> (the
      larger of the two lower leg bones). These two bones sit next
      to each other and are free to rotate about a single axis. A
      mechanism is needed to keep the two legs bones attached to
      each other, while still allowing rotation. In the case of
      the human knee this is achieved with a four-bar linkage
      consisting of the two bones together with the <a
      href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_cruciate_ligament">anterior
      cruciate ligament (ACL)</a> and <a
      href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_cruciate_ligament">posterior
      cruciate ligament (PCL)</a>, as shown below.
    </p>

    <PrairieDrawCanvas id="aml-fk-c" width="600" height="596" class="figureImage">
      <p class="controls">
        <button class="option-toggle:aml-fk-c:showLinkage" onclick="aml_fk_c.toggleOption('showLinkage')">show linkage</button>
        <button class="anim-toggle:aml-fk-c" onclick="aml_fk_c.toggleAnim()">animation</button>
        <button class="reset-time:aml-fk-c" onclick="aml_fk_c.resetTime()">reset</button>
      </p>
      <p class="figureCaption">
        <i> An <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_resonance_imaging">MRI</a> image of a <a
        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sagittal_plane">sagittal
        section</a> through a human <a
        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knee">knee joint</a>,
        showing the <a
        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_cruciate_ligament">ACL</a>
        and <a
        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posterior_cruciate_ligament">PCL</a>
        ligaments.  Image credit: <a
        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:MRT_ACL_PCL_01.jpg">Wikimedia
        Commons image</a> (<a
        href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/deed.en">CC
        BY-SA 2.0</a>). </i>
      </p>
      <p>
        The four-bar model of the knee is only approximate, and
        neglects many important mechanical features. In particular,
        the ACL and PCL are not rigid rods, and can only provide
        tensile forces (they act as mechanical ropes). The
        compressive force is actually provided by the <a
        href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meniscus_(anatomy)">meniscus</a>
        that separates the femur and tibia bones. In the simple
        four-bar knee model shown here, the rigid rods include the
        effects of both the ligaments and the meniscus.
      </p>
    </PrairieDrawCanvas>

