    <CalloutContainer slot="cards">
      <CalloutCard>
        <p>
          No joints in the human body have the rotating bone fully
          constrained by the enclosing socket bone. Instead, like
          the knee, they have a partial socket or cylinder and the
          rotating bone is held in place by ligaments. This type of
          arrangement is typical for most animals, with one rare
          exception being the <a
          href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_badger">European
          Badger (Meles Meles)</a>. In older badgers, the jaw
          rotates on an entirely enclosed pivot, as shown
          below. This means that the badger cannot waggle its jaw
          side-to-side as humans can, and also means that the badger
          jaw cannot be dislocated or disconnected without breaking
          the bone.
        </p>
